{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f42a47d4-6f5c-4830-8c85-9d5f79a4a954","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\nHere's the difference:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** – Downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads, aligning them with your current SDK version. This is what you want after an SDK update.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** – Re-installs the workloads you already have *at their current versions*. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but doesn't fetch newer packages.\n\nSince your SDK moved forward but your workloads didn't, `update` will pull the matching MAUI workload bits for the new SDK. After running it, do a clean build:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet clean\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf issues persist, check `dotnet workload list` to confirm `maui` (or `maui-*`) workloads are present.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"93a2854a-db76-4bd8-b431-9e31a40d169b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix a .NET MAUI build issue after an SDK update. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search files or run commands.","outputTokens":274,"requestId":"9423:1DC2AE:1494B1B:16F9CEB:6A06703A"},"id":"47063d58-93f1-4014-91fb-a26a81575f10","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:00:49.941Z","parentId":"8df463ba-0eb4-4d96-a657-30b7c9225f5e"}
